Europe
------
[1] ECDC (update)
Date: Mon 4 Feb 2013
Source: European Centre for disease control and Prevention (ECDC) News Portal [edited]
http://ecdc.europa.eu/en/press/news/Lists/News/ECDC_DispForm.aspx?List=32e43ee8-e230-4424-a783-85742124029a&ID=741


The latest ECDC report on measles and rubella shows that 8326 cases of measles were reported by 29 EU [European Union] and EEA [European Economic Area] countries from January to November 2012. France, Italy, Romania, Spain, and the United Kingdom accounted for 87 per cent of all reported cases, and there were no measles-related deaths during this timeframe. However, 7 cases were complicated by acute measles encephalitis.

Although the number of reported cases was substantially lower in 2012 than in the same period in 2011, measles transmission has continued at the European level.

[The incidence of rubella data provides an indirect estimate of the success of the measles vaccination campaigns in the region, since the vaccine universally used is the triple MMR: measles, mumps, and rubella (MMR) vaccine. - Mod.CP]. In total, 28 536 cases of rubella were reported during the period December 2011 to November 2012 by the 26 EU and EEA reporting countries. Poland and Romania accounted for 99 per cent of all reported rubella cases in the 12 month period. Reported cases in 2012 are higher than for the same period in 2011, and the highest notification rate was among adolescents between 15 and 19 years of age.

Measles and rubella are targeted for elimination in Europe by 2015. ECDC closely monitors progress towards interruption of endemic transmission of both diseases through enhanced surveillance and epidemic intelligence. Measles and rubella vaccinations are routinely delivered in the form of the MMR vaccine in Europe, and the 1st of the 2 recommended doses is normally given during the 2nd year of life.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The ECDC report indicates that whereas transmission of measles virus infection in Europe remains low, rubella virus infection is on the rise. This is somewhat unexpected in view of the fact that the same MMR triple vaccine that is used to protect against both diseases simultaneously is universally available. This situation may presumably be a consequence of different policies and priorities in the various EU/EEA countries. - Mod.CP]

******
[2] UK (HPA report)
Date: Fri 8 Feb 2013
Source: Health Protection Agency Report 2013; 7(6) [abbreviated, edited]
http://www.hpa.org.uk/hpr/archives/2013/news0613.htm#msls


The number of laboratory confirmed cases of measles with onset dates in 2012 is 2016 (provisional), the highest annual total since 1994, when enhanced laboratory confirmation began.

From January [2012], the monthly totals increased to peak in May 2012, decreased during the summer, and then increased again after schools returned in September 2012. Almost 70 per cent (1374/2016) of all cases were in children between the ages of one and 18 years with the highest proportion occurring in those under 5 years of age. Only 92 (6.7 per cent) of the cases aged under 19 had documented receipt of at least one dose of measles-containing vaccine.

More than 40 per cent of the cases in 2012 were reported in the North West region. During the 1st half of the year, cases were mainly associated with a large ongoing community outbreak in Cheshire & Merseyside suspected to be fuelled by transmission among preschool children. In the 2nd half of 2012, cases were more widely distributed across the North West in association with several clusters in schools.

The 2nd highest number of cases were reported from the South East region, where they were mainly part of a community-wide outbreak in Sussex, which started in the Steiner community in 2011 and continued into 2012 amongst unvaccinated school-age children.

Since the end of July 2012, many cases were linked to an outbreak in travelling communities that has affected almost all regions in England and Wales. In the latter part of the year, the cases outside the travelling communities were associated with nurseries and school outbreaks across Wales, North West and South West regions.

Throughout the EU [European Union] and EEA [European Economic Area] countries, there were 7392 measles cases reported between January and November 2012. The UK, along with France, Italy, Romania, and Spain, accounted for 87 per cent of these cases. Although no deaths occurred in the period across Europe, 7 cases of acute measles encephalitis were reported.

