[4] UK (Sussex)
Date: Sun 10 Feb 2013
Source: The Argus [abbreviated & edited]
http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/10217804.Sussex_among_worst_areas_affected_by_measles_outbreak/


A measles outbreak across Sussex has contributed to the highest level of cases nationally for 18 years. There were 330 confirmed cases of the disease in the county during 2012, although the actual number is higher because samples are not taken from every patient. Brighton and Hove was the worst affected with 195 people falling ill, while East Sussex had 90 and West Sussex 45. The outbreak made up a significant part of the 2016 confirmed cases in England and Wales throughout the year [2012], according to figures from the Health Protection Agency (see part [2] above).

The increase is blamed on poor take up rates for the measles, mumps, and rubella vaccine (MMR). Around 95 per cent of a community needs to have both doses of the jab in order for it to have the best protection against the virus spreading.

HPA head of immunisation Mary Ramsay said: "Coverage of MMR is now at historically high levels, but measles is highly infectious and can spread easily among communities that are poorly vaccinated and can affect anyone who is susceptible, including toddlers in whom vaccination has been delayed. Measles continues to circulate in several European countries that are popular with holidaymakers. It is often associated with being a disease of the past and, as a result, people may be unaware that it is a dangerous infection that can lead to death in severe cases."

