[9] Taiwan (ex Hunan)
Date: Sat 9 Feb 2013
Source: Focus Taiwan News Channel [edited]
http://focustaiwan.tw/ShowNews/WebNews_Detail.aspx?Type=aALL&ID=201302090009


Heath authorities have confirmed the 1st case in Taiwan this year [2013] of measles contracted overseas, an 8 month old girl who returned from China in early February 2013. The baby developed a rash and fever in late January 2013 during a trip to Hunan province in China with her mother to visit relatives, said Chou Jih-haw, deputy director-general of the Department of Health's Centers for Disease Control (CDC).

When the child and mother returned to Taiwan on 2 Feb 2013, an alert was triggered on the airport's body temperature equipment, and the baby was subsequently hospitalized and quarantined, Chou said. The patient is recovering, the CDC added. Health authorities have been tracking the other passengers on the flight from [mainland] China and monitoring the staff at the hospital that admitted the child, but there have been no other cases of measles so far, the CDC said.

The number of confirmed cases of measles in [mainland] China was 1501 in January 2013, more than 3.5 times the number for the same month last year [2012], according to the CDC. Visits to areas where measles is common are not advisable for children under one year old, Chou said. But if such visits are necessary, the children should be vaccinated before travel, he added. The Taiwan government provides free vaccinations against measles, mumps, and rubella for children one year old and over.

[byline: Chen Ching-fang and Elaine Hou]

