The Americas
------------
[10] USA (CA ex India)
Date: Mon 4 Feb 2013
Source: Central Coast News [edited]
http://www.kionrightnow.com/story/20953695/santa-cruz-county-vaccinates-workers-after-measles-cases


Two rare cases of measles on the Central Coast have public health officials acting quickly to keep it from spreading. On Sunday [3 Feb 2013], we went to find out who may have been exposed and how you can stay protected.

The Santa Cruz Public Health Department said if you were at New Leaf Market or Liberty Bank in Felton on 26, 28, or 29 Jan 2013, you may have been exposed to measles. Store manager Mike Macallair said the daughter of an employee recently took a trip to India without being vaccinated and came back with the disease. "She came down with it after they figured out what it was, and she had a mild infection, but she had come to work several days," said Felton New Leaf Market store manager Mike Macallair. So they contacted public health right away. Every employee was tested, and most were immune. But several weren't, and on Sunday [3 Feb 2013], they were given an immunization to make sure [the virus] doesn't spread.

At New Leaf Market, if customers are concerned, they're being given a sheet of paper with information on exposure to measles. So how do you know whether you're not at risk? Public health officials said there are 3 ways persons can be protected: "By having had their 2 measles shots growing up, by being born before 1957, or by having been in the Army," said Santa Cruz County Public Health interim director Dr Ira Lubell.

Typical symptoms are a cough, fever, watery eyes, runny nose, white spots in the mouth, and a rash. County public health said the last time they had a few cases was in 2005. "Santa Cruz has always had one of the lowest community immunization participation rates in the state," said Dr Lubell. Measles can be deadly for anyone. But Santa Cruz County Public Health officials said it's even more dangerous for anyone who is pregnant or who has a weak immune system.

[byline: Marissa Pendergrass]

--
